locates them and Powell saves Barry from Bohannan who is armed with an accelerated Exo-Skeleton suit. Powell then decides to reveal his secret identity to the world.\n |LineColor=B30000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=17\n |Title=Captain Cold\n |DirectedBy=Gilbert Shilton\n |WrittenBy={{StoryTeleplay|s=Paul De Meo &amp; Gail Morgan Hickman|t=Gail Morgan Hickman}}\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|4|6}}\n |ShortSummary=Mobster Jimmy Swain employs hitman Leonard Wynters, also known as \&quot;[[Captain Cold]]\&quot; for his weapon of choice, a nuclear-powered freeze ray, to eliminate his competitors and then the Flash. Barry&#39;s investigation is hampered by Terri Kronenberg, a tabloid reporter for the National Inquisitor. After killing Swain for firing him after his failure to kill The Flash in the first attempt, Wynters nearly kills Barry after Kronenberg gets in the middle of them during a confrontation. Wynters is caught by The Flash after he attempts to kill her in her apartment. Wynters later escapes prison and lures the Flash into a trap, hellbent on completing his contract out of honor, but Barry outsmarts him due to a device that preserves his body heat, and diverts Wynters&#39; beam against him, encasing Wynters in ice.\n |LineColor=B30000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=18\n |Title=Twin Streaks\n |DirectedBy=[[James A. Contner]]\n |WrittenBy=Stephen Hattman\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|4|13}}\n |ShortSummary=Barry is cloned by Dr. Jason Brassel, who names the clone \&quot;Pollux\&quot;, who Brassel designs a blue variant suit for. Upon learning that he is a clone and not a real person, Pollux goes on a rampage and comes into conflict with the Flash, who is currently suffering symptoms of stress and fatigue. Brassel attempts to kill Barry after Pollux throws a bullet into him, but Pollux takes the bullet and dies in Barry&#39;s arms, while Brassel succumbs from the injuries Pollux had earlier inflicted on him.\n |LineColor=B30000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=19\n |Title=Done with Mirrors\n |DirectedBy=Danny Bilson\n |WrittenBy=Howard Chaykin &amp; John Francis Moore\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|4|27}}\n |ShortSummary=[[Mirror Master|Sam Scudder]], a criminal mastermind who uses mirrors and holograms to commit his crimes, steals an advanced battery from S.T.A.R Labs Silicon Valley division, which is then stolen from him by his partner, Anastasia Masters, who flees to Central City and seduces her former classmate Barry into sheltering her at his apartment. Scudder kidnaps both Barry and Tina&#39;s mother Jocelyn Weller, whom he mistakes for Stasia&#39;s buyer, to force Stasia to deliver the battery, and Barry ultimately realizes Stasia is manipulating him. He rescues Tina, who had been lured to the station where Stasia was trying to sell the battery, pummels Scudder and arrests Stasia, returning the battery to S.T.A.R Labs. |LineColor=B30000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=20\n |Title=Good Night, Central City\n |DirectedBy=Mario Azzopardi\n |WrittenBy=Jim Trombetta\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|5|4}}\n |ShortSummary=Petty crook Harry Milgrim and his cousin, scientist Roger Braintree, plan to use a soundwave device developed by Braintree, which places people in an induced slumber, to rob Central City. Milgrim fakes his death during a test run, then pins the blame for a robbery on Barry, who races against time to both prove his innocence and prevent Milgrim, Braintree and a group of professional gangsters from conducting a citywide robbery after discovering the induced sleep is fatal if the sleepers sleep too long. In the end, Barry triumphs, with Milgrim, who had killed Braintree, is arrested, clearing his name, and humiliating an over eager internal affairs agent.\n |LineColor=B30000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=21\n |Title=Alpha\n |DirectedBy=[[Bruce Bilson]]\n |WrittenBy={{StoryTeleplay|s=Gail Morgan Hickman &amp; Denise Skinner|t=Gail Morgan Hickman}}\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|5|11}}\n |ShortSummary=Barry and Tina befriend Alpha, an android assassin developed by the NSIA a United States government division who refuses to kill, and protect her from another android assassin, Omega, send to destroy her. The Flash ultimately destroys Omega and helps Alpha evade the NSIA and escape Central City before a bomb inside her goes off.  Later she leaves to start her life anew.\n |LineColor=B30000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=22\n |Title=The Trial of the Trickster\n |DirectedBy=Danny Bilson\n |WrittenBy=Howard Chaykin &amp; John Francis Moore\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1991|5|18}}\n |ShortSummary=James Jesse is brought to trial for his previous rampage in Central City. Jesse later escapes from the courtroom with help from an obsessive fan, Zoey Clark, and becomes the Trickster once again, with Clark as his assistant, Prank. They brainwash the Flash into joining them in wreaking havoc, damaging the Flash&#39;s public image, but Jesse ultimately betrays Clark and leaves her to the police. Tina and Megan join forces and manage to break Barry free in time to prevent Jesse from executing the lawyers and the Judge involved in his trial. Jesse is then captured and put into a padded cell, while the Flash is embraced as a hero by the people of Central City. Barry turns down an offer to move to San Francisco with Megan because he is not ready to say goodbye to Central City.\n |LineColor=B30000\n}}\n}}\n\n==Release==\n===Broadcast===\n&#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; was originally scheduled to debut on [[CBS]] in the 8{{nbsp}}pm ([[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]) slot on Thursday, to go against &#39;&#39;[[The Cosby Show]]&#39;&#39; on [[NBC]], in an attempt to attract younger viewers, before [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] moved &#39;&#39;[[The Simpsons]]&#39;&#39; from Sunday to the Thursday 8&amp;nbsp;pm slot for the same reason. After debuting on September 20, 1990, at 8&amp;nbsp;pm, CBS moved the series to 8:30{{nbsp}}pm with its second episode, in an attempt to broadcast opposite less formidable competition in Fox&#39;s &#39;&#39;[[Babes (TV series)|Babes]]&#39;&#39;, NBC&#39;s &#39;&#39;[[A Different World]]&#39;&#39; and the second half-hour of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]&#39;s &#39;&#39;Father Dowling Mysteries&#39;&#39;.&lt;ref name=\&quot;LATimes\&quot; /&gt; Eventually, CBS moved the series off Thursdays entirely, moving the show to Saturday nights.&lt;ref name=\&quot;CBBin\&quot; /&gt; Had the show continued, it was revealed the second season would have opened with the Flash&#39;s rogues teaming up to take down the hero.&lt;ref name=\&quot;CBBin\&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book |title=Age Of TV Heroes: The Live-Action Adventures Of Your Favorite Comic Book Characters |last=Hofius |first=Jason |authorlink= |author2=George Khoury  |year=2010 |publisher=TwoMorrows Publishing |location= |isbn=1-60549-010-5 |page= |pages= |url= }}&lt;/ref&gt;\n&lt;!--The unusual 8:30 slot did not work and the series floundered when moved to 9&amp;nbsp;pm. The remaining episodes aired on Saturday nights where it faced cancellation after a single season. A brief attempt at rerunning the series in the summer on Fridays in hopes of finding an audience and reversing the cancellation also failed.--&gt;\n\n===Marketing===\n[[Warner Bros. Television]] and CBS began its promotion of the series in July 1990 during the [[1990 NBA All-Star Game]]. It also had ad campaigns on radio and cable television during \&quot;wrestling matches on [[USA Network|USA Cable]] and during [&#39;&#39;[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]&#39;&#39; airings] on [[The Family Channel (American TV network, founded 1990)|the Family Channel]]\&quot;, as well as ads in [[The Flash (comic book)|&#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; comic book]] and posters for the series in malls and [[Kmart]]s across the country. Four-minute promos of the series aired at all [[Six Flags]] amusement parks and a few weeks before the pilot&#39;s debut, Warner Bros. flew banners over beaches on both coasts. Describing the marketing, George Schweitzer, senior vice president of communications at the CBS Broadcast Group said, \&quot;It&#39;s not being sold as a comic book. It&#39;s being sold like &#39;&#39;Batman&#39;&#39; [the 1989 film] \u2013 dark and mysterious and exciting. The promos have a theatrical quality.\&quot; The pilot debuted on July 15, 1990 at a \&quot;big bash\&quot; at the Warner Bros. Burbank lot.&lt;ref name=\&quot;LATimes\&quot; /&gt;\n\n=== Home media ===\n&#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; was released on DVD in January 2006.&lt;ref name=\&quot;CBBin\&quot; /&gt;\n\nSeveral episodes were edited as three TV movies and released on VHS:\n* &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; (1990). The 2-hour pilot episode.\n* &#39;&#39;The Flash II: Revenge of the Trickster&#39;&#39; (1991). Formed by the episodes \&quot;The Trickster\&quot; and \&quot;The Trial of the Trickster\&quot;\n* &#39;&#39;The Flash III: Deadly Nightshade&#39;&#39; (1991). Formed by  the episodes \&quot;Ghost in the Machine\&quot; and \&quot;The Deadly Nightshade\&quot;.\n\nLaser-disc:\n* &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; (1990). The 2-hour pilot episode.\n\n==Other media==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2015}}\n\n=== Comic book ===\nA comic book tie-in special based on the TV series was published by [[DC Comics]] in 1991 titled &#39;&#39;The Flash TV Special&#39;&#39; #1, running at 76 pages. It features two stories, one written by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] with art by Javier Saltares, and the second written by then-writer of the ongoing &#39;&#39;Flash&#39;&#39; (vol. 2) title, [[Mark Waid]] featuring a thief Kid Flash; plus a behind-the-scenes look on the making of the TV series with photos.\n\n=== Video game ===\nA video game was released for [[Game Boy]] in 1991 by [[THQ]], and was based on the TV series. It was released in the US and had a password system. [[The Flash (video game)|A second game]] was programmed by [[Probe Entertainment]] and released only in Europe for the [[Master System]] in 1993.\n\n==Arrowverse==\n{{Main|The Flash (2014 TV series)|Elseworlds (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)}}\nThe 2014 television series, &#39;&#39;[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]&#39;&#39;, features several references to the 1990 series. John Wesley Shipp plays the recurring role of [[Barry Allen (Arrowverse)|Barry Allen]]&#39;s father, [[Henry Allen (Arrowverse)|Henry Allen]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/flash-barry-allens-father-john-wesley-shipp-707359|title=&#39;Flash&#39;: John Wesley Shipp&#39;s Secret Character Revealed|last=Ng|first=Philiana|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 27, 2014|accessdate=May 28, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; and Amanda Pays once again portrays a character named Dr. [[Tina McGee (Arrowverse)|Tina McGee]].&lt;ref name=\&quot;Pays\&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/flash-amanda-pays-reprising-tina-732946|title=The CW&#39;s &#39;The Flash&#39; Recruits Original Star for Flashy Reunion|last=Ng|first=Philiana|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 15, 2014|accessdate=September 15, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; Shipp eventually portrays the [[Earth-3 (Arrowverse)|Earth-3]] version of Henry Allen, [[Jay Garrick (Arrowverse)|Jay Garrick / Flash]]. Regarding the difference in his portrayal of Garrick over Allen, Shipp \&quot;figured Jay is my version of Barry\&quot; from the 1990 series, adding, \&quot;I went back and I watched a couple of episodes of the 1990/91 version to kind of remind myself what I did. [Jay] is much more reminiscent of my Barry Allen from 25 years ago than my Henry Allen. I went back and I was amazed how much attitude my Barry Allen had in some situations. I went back and I picked up that thread and I brought it forward 25 years, and tried to weave it in.\&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/dc/2016/10/02/the-flashs-john-wesley-shipp-jay-is-my-version-of-barry-25-years/|title=The Flash&#39;s John Wesley Shipp: \&quot;Jay Is My Version of Barry, 25 Years Later\&quot;|last=Burlingame|first=Russ|publisher=Comicbook.com|date=October 2, 2016|accessdate=October 4, 2016}}&lt;/ref&gt; In \&quot;[[Welcome to Earth-2]]\&quot;, as Barry, [[Cisco Ramon (Arrowverse)|Cisco Ramon]] and [[Harry Wells (Arrowverse)|Harry Wells]] are traveling to [[Earth-2 (Arrowverse)|Earth-2]], glimpses of the multiverse are seen, including an image of Shipp as the Flash from the 1990 series, implying that the series was retroactively being added to the [[Arrowverse]]-multiverse.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/article/flash-teases-dc-tv-future-retro-continuity-with-multiple-surprise-cameos|title=\&quot;Flash\&quot; Teases DC TV Future, Retro Continuity With Multiple Surprise Cameos|last=Couto|first=Anthony|publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nIn the episode \&quot;[[Tricksters (The Flash)|Tricksters]]\&quot;, Mark Hamill returns as [[James Jesse (Arrowverse)|James Jesse / Trickster]], with images of Hamill as Trickster from the 1990 TV series being used in a police report, and Vito D&#39;Ambrosio plays Mayor [[Anthony Bellows]]; a variation of a police officer character he played in 1991, though a later episode revealed Mayor Bellows was formerly an officer.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/exclusive-mark-hamill-to-play-the-trickster-again-on-the-flash|title=Exclusive: Mark Hamill to play the Trickster again on &#39;The Flash&#39;|publisher=Hitfix|last=Sepinwall|first=Alan|date=December 8, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/tv/the-flash-recap-tricksters-mark-hamill-115179930095.html|title=&#39;The Flash&#39; Recap: At Last\u2026 the Joker|last=Chan|first=Robert|publisher=Yahoo!|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=August 8, 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt; 2014 series composer [[Blake Neely]] incorporated Walker&#39;s theme for the Trickster into the episode.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cowonthewall/status/583098232651190272|title=It was an honor and great fun to use the great Shirley Walker&#39;s \&quot;Trickster\&quot; theme tonight! Also a life-long dream to score @HamillHimself.|last=Neely|first=Blake|publisher=Twitter|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=August 8, 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt; Alex D\u00e9sert reprises the role of Julio Mendez in the series&#39; third-season episode, \&quot;[[Flashpoint (The Flash episode)|Flashpoint]]\&quot;, where he is the captain of the Central City Police Department in the [[Flashpoint (comics)|Flashpoint]] timeline.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/flash-star-alex-desert-playing-captain-julio-mendez-season-3-premiere-flashpoint-2427223|title=&#39;The Flash&#39; Star Alex D\u00e9sert On Playing Captain Julio Mendez in Season 3 Premiere, &#39;Flashpoint&#39;|last=Saclao|first=Christian|publisher=International Business Times|date=October 6, 2016|accessdate=October 9, 2016}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Corinne Bohrer]] reprises her role as [[Zoey Clark (Arrowverse)|Zoey Clark / Prank]] in the fourth season episode, \&quot;[[The Elongated Knight Rises]],\&quot; which also featured stills of her from the 1990 show in her police file.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/flash-tv-corinne-bohrer-prank-guest/|title=The Flash Brings Back Another Actor (and Character) From 1990 Series|last=Melrose|first=Kevin|publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=January 23, 2018|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nShipp reprises his role as Barry Allen from this series in the 2018 Arrowverse crossover, \&quot;[[Elseworlds (Arrowverse)|Elseworlds]]\&quot;.&lt;ref name=\&quot;Shipp90sFlash\&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/elseworlds-image-john-wesley-shipp/|title=New \u2018Elseworlds\u2019 Image Sees John Wesley Shipp Getting in on the Arrowverse Crossover Madness|last=Mancuso|first=Vinnie|publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=October 22, 2018|accessdate=October 22, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/73N0yygJq?url=http://collider.com/elseworlds-image-john-wesley-shipp/|archivedate=October 23, 2018|url-status = live}}&lt;/ref&gt; The crossover also links the 1990 series to the Arrowverse, designating its world as [[Earth-90 (Arrowverse)|Earth-90]].&lt;ref name=\&quot;Earth90\&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/12/02/supergirl-post-credit-scene-elseworlds-crossover/|title=Supergirl post-credit scene teases the Monitor&#39;s plan in &#39;Elseworlds&#39; crossover|last=Agard|first=Chancellor|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=December 2, 2018|accessdate=December 5, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/74Ren9lAa?url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/12/02/supergirl-post-credit-scene-elseworlds-crossover/|archivedate=December 5, 2018|url-status = live}}&lt;/ref&gt; Danny Elfman&#39;s theme accompanied the Earth-90 Flash&#39;s appearance into the episodes.&lt;ref&gt;http://collider.com/elseworlds-references-explained/amp/&lt;/ref&gt; He attempts to warn the heroes of [[Earth-1 (Arrowverse)|Earth-1]] about [[Monitor (Arrowverse)|Mar Novu / The Monitor]] to prevent a similar devastation that his own world suffered before Novu breaches him away. The character reappears in the following year&#39;s crossover, [[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|\&quot;Crisis on Infinite Earths\&quot;]], having been captured by the [[Anti-Monitor (Arrowverse)|Anti-Monitor]] and forced to power his anti-matter cannon to destroy the multiverse. Despite being freed by Earth-1 Flash and his allies, he ultimately sacrifices himself to destroy the machine, seeing his life with Tina (whom he had married at some point) flash before his eyes in the form of a clip from the original series.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |last1=Dowling |first1=Amber |title=\u2018Crisis on Infinite Earths\u2019 Recap: A Rewritten Destiny Brings Another Superhero Death |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/crisis-on-infinite-earths-part-three-recap-flash-black-lightning-huntress-1203432498/ |website=Variety |language=en |date=11 December 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; After the filming of the scene, John Wesley Shipp told &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; showrunner Eric Wallace, \&quot;Thank you for giving me this opportunity to close a chapter.\&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/11/crisis-on-infinite-earths-the-flash-earth-90-death/|title=&#39;Crisis on Infinite Earths&#39; bosses unpack The Flash&#39;s sacrifice and that emotional footage|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\n== See also ==\n* &#39;&#39;[[Birds of Prey (TV series)|Birds of Prey]]&#39;&#39;\n* &#39;&#39;[[Justice League of America (film)|Justice League of America]]&#39;&#39;\n* &#39;&#39;[[Aquaman (TV pilot)|Aquaman]]&#39;&#39;\n* &#39;&#39;[[Super Friends]]&#39;&#39;\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0098798|title=The Flash}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-flash|The Flash}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0101893|title=The Flash II: Revenge of the Trickster}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0206752|title=Flash III: Deadly Nightshade}}\n* [http://www.scifi.com/freezone/flash/flash.pdf Episode Guide from SciFi.com]\n* [http://thefastestmanalive.blogspot.com/ Crimson Lightning] - A blog featuring regular reviews of &#39;&#39;The Flash&#39;&#39; television series.\n* [http://www.bigfanboy.com/pages/interviews/johnshipp/shipp.html Interview about the series with lead actor John Wesley Shipp]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060615064113/http://dmgutierrez.com/podcasts.html Pet Fly Podcast Page] Including a downloadable commentary track in which series developers Danny Bilson and Paul De Meo discuss the \&quot;Trial of the Trickster\&quot; episode\n* [http://www.hyperborea.org/flash/tv.html The TV series on Hyperborea]\n\n{{Flash}}\n{{DC Comics TV}}\n{{Arrowverse}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flash (1990 TV series), The}}\n[[Category:1990 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1990s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:1991 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:CBS original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television shows]]\n[[Category:Flash (comics) television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Warner Bros. Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Arrowverse television series]]&quot;</span>
